tors of the Dene to undertake a trek from the present-day Northwest Territories to Arizona. Inuit migrated across the Arctic from Siberia, reaching Southern Labrador, where they met Basque fishers from northern Spain.As early as the fifteenth century, fishing ships from western Europe were coming to Newfoundland for cod, creating the greatest transatlantic maritime link in the early modern world. Later, fur traders would take capitalism across the continent, using cheap rum to lubricate their transactions. The contributors to Before Canada reveal the latest findings of archaeological and historical research on this fascinating period. Along the way, they reframe the story of the Canadian past, extending its limits across time and space and challenging us to reconsider our assumptions about this supposedly young country.Innovative and multidisciplinary, Before Canada inspires interest in the deep history of northern North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHistory, Modern-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh  aApache.  aAthabaska.  aDene.  aHaklyut.  aIndigenous.  aInuit.  aJesuits.  aLabrador.  aNewfoundland.  aPaul LeJeune.  aSt Lawrence.  aarchaeology.  alithic.  amocassins.1 aBouchard, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Adrian L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerksen, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewar, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGates St-Pierre, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreer, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul